<h1>🕹️ RS003 Week 7 — English Worksheet</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Fly the Ship in Four Directions · <strong>Course:</strong> Pygame Space Shooter · <strong>Time:</strong> about 45 minutes</p>
<p>This week you think about how the ship <strong>flies</strong> up, down, left, and right while you hold the arrow keys. You read the code, predict what it does, fix broken code, and explain it in your own words — including the code you wrote in today's live lesson.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>🧠 Words to know: <strong>X axis</strong>, <strong>Y axis</strong>, <strong>key press</strong>, <strong>increase / decrease</strong>, <strong>speed</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each piece of code. Write what you think it does. You do not run anything — just think it through.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">ship_x = CENTER_X
ship_y = HEIGHT - 100
SPEED = 5
ship_x -= SPEED
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Does <code>ship_x -= 5</code> move the ship left or right? Why?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">keys = pygame.key.get_pressed()
if keys[pygame.K_LEFT]:  ship_x -= SPEED
if keys[pygame.K_RIGHT]: ship_x += SPEED
if keys[pygame.K_UP]:    ship_y -= SPEED
if keys[pygame.K_DOWN]:  ship_y += SPEED
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What happens while you hold UP? What about holding DOWN? Why does UP make <code>ship_y</code> smaller?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">pygame.draw.rect(screen, CYAN, (ship_x - 20, ship_y, 40, 50))
pygame.draw.polygon(screen, WHITE, [(ship_x, ship_y - 20), (ship_x - 20, ship_y), (ship_x + 20, ship_y)])
</code></pre>
<p><strong>The body and nose both use <code>ship_x</code> and <code>ship_y</code>. When you press a key, what moves?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">SPEED = 2
SPEED = 10
</code></pre>
<p><strong>One of these makes the ship fly slowly and one makes it fly fast. Which is which, and why?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each block below was meant to do something but is broken. Write the fixed code, then explain why the original was wrong.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — Pressing UP should move the ship up, but it moves <strong>down</strong> instead.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">if keys[pygame.K_UP]:
    ship_y += SPEED
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> up means Y gets smaller.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — The ship should only move <strong>while a key is held</strong>, but it drifts to the right on its own without any key press.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">ship_x += SPEED
if keys[pygame.K_LEFT]:
    ship_x -= SPEED
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the first line runs every loop no matter what.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — The keys do nothing at all. The ship never moves.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">for event in pygame.event.get():
    if event.type == pygame.QUIT:
        running = False
    if keys[pygame.K_LEFT]:
        ship_x -= SPEED
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> <code>keys</code> was never asked for. You need <code>pygame.key.get_pressed()</code> outside the event loop.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code (show where <code>keys</code> is set and used):</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Explain the Code 📖</h2>
<p>Here is the full working program from this week. Read it carefully and answer the questions below. You do not need to run it.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">import pygame
pygame.init()

WIDTH, HEIGHT = 800, 600
CENTER_X = WIDTH // 2
screen = pygame.display.set_mode((WIDTH, HEIGHT))

SPACE = (10, 12, 40)
CYAN = (80, 220, 255)
WHITE = (255, 255, 255)
RED = (230, 60, 60)

ship_x = CENTER_X
ship_y = HEIGHT - 100
SPEED = 5

clock = pygame.time.Clock()
running = True
while running:
    for event in pygame.event.get():
        if event.type == pygame.QUIT:
            running = False

    keys = pygame.key.get_pressed()
    if keys[pygame.K_LEFT]:  ship_x -= SPEED
    if keys[pygame.K_RIGHT]: ship_x += SPEED
    if keys[pygame.K_UP]:    ship_y -= SPEED
    if keys[pygame.K_DOWN]:  ship_y += SPEED

    screen.fill(SPACE)
    pygame.draw.rect(screen, CYAN, (ship_x - 20, ship_y, 40, 50))
    pygame.draw.polygon(screen, WHITE, [(ship_x, ship_y - 20), (ship_x - 20, ship_y), (ship_x + 20, ship_y)])
    pygame.draw.rect(screen, RED, (ship_x - 16, ship_y + 50, 8, 10))
    pygame.draw.rect(screen, RED, (ship_x + 8, ship_y + 50, 8, 10))
    pygame.display.flip()
    clock.tick(60)

pygame.quit()
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What do <code>ship_x</code> and <code>ship_y</code> hold, and what is the starting position of the ship?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>What does <code>keys = pygame.key.get_pressed()</code> give you, and why is it inside the <code>while</code> loop?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why does the same <code>ship_x</code> and <code>ship_y</code> appear in the body, the nose, and both thrusters?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>What would change on screen if you set <code>SPEED = 10</code> instead of <code>5</code>?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why is <code>screen.fill(SPACE)</code> called every loop before the ship is drawn?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

